From @sstroeer, Vowell Glacier, Bugaboo Provincial Park, British Columbia: "The Bugaboos are a trad climbers dream come true: perfect splitters in high quality granite, in a spectacular setting far removed from the hustle of the outside world. Short of hiring a helicopter, the only way to get in here is to drive 50km on a dirt road and then hike another three hours from the trailhead to arrive at Applebee Campground, the traditional staging ground for most climbers who are eyeing objectives on Bugaboo and Snowpatch Spire."
Winter still going strong in the Tetons. Photo: @woodylowder / @jhmtnguides.

"An impressive crevasse we stumbled upon whilst crossing the Stikine Ice Cap. For me, this is Mother Nature at her majestic best. As beautiful as it is imposing, these huge types of crevasse are not as dangerous as they may appear at first glance. During an expedition such as this one, anything we see clearly is a lot less dangerous than hidden snow bridges, which we may find higher up, for example. This was close to sea level and it was raw ice, so there were no snow bridges. This photo exemplifies my feelings of vulnerability when faced with the Earth’s dramatically, exposed crust." Words by @vincentcolliard, photo by @borgeousland.

node.text: "Until this winter, I had not tasted ice climbing of the Midwestern flavor. And so, as we sped down state roads that seemed laid out in cardinal directions regardless of the frequent hills, I found myself wondering: Why Munising? And more broadly: why ice festivals?" @freddiewilkinson reports from the #MichiganIceFest, an annual gathering of the many characters of ice climbing. Full story on the blog. Link in bio. From @mikelibecki: "We quickly gained 1500 feet of mellow climbing and set up our high camp perched on a small ledge. Soon I watched @ethan_pringle onsight, on first ascent terrain, a 5.13 pitch, something only the best climbers in the world could pull off. Ethan was on fire and quickly led several more pitches to the summit as I belayed. Supporting Ethan to onsight this climb was an honor and privilege. A 20-hour push put us on the summit, trying to stay awake while peering at the Greenland icecap as the last light of the almost-24-hour sun faded." Check out the full story of Mike and Ethan's recent first ascent in Greenland on our blog (link in bio). Photo: @andy_mann.

On February 3, @mountainhardwear athlete Sunny Stroeer (@sstroeer) became the first woman to complete the Aconcagua 360 - a circumnavigation and summit of the Seven Summits' second tallest mountain... in a single push. Sunny finished in 47 hours and 30 minutes. Huge congrats to Sunny on this incredible feat. Photos: @julian_kusi and @sstroeer.
